WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:04.240
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
welcome everybody.

00:00:04.240 --> 00:00:07.570
Welcome to a conversation I'm
going to have with a woman

00:00:07.570 --> 00:00:09.460
I admire very much.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:10.880
Ellen Gustafson.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:14.750
And she has just
released "We the Eaters."

00:00:14.750 --> 00:00:18.270
She is quite a powerful woman.

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:20.590
And she's put
together two things--

00:00:20.590 --> 00:00:24.620
food and writing-- which
are usually very quiet,

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:30.110
small things in this small book
with a very powerful message.

00:00:30.110 --> 00:00:32.130
And it's pretty revolutionary.

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:33.886
So I want to welcome
you to Google.

00:00:33.886 --> 00:00:35.010
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Thank you.

00:00:35.010 --> 00:00:35.740
FEMALE SPEAKER: And
thank you for coming.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:37.760
ELLEN GUSTAFSON:
Thanks for having me.

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:42.060
FEMALE SPEAKER: So why
should we be eating.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:43.740
And even more
important than that,

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:46.820
why should we be
eating dinner-- which

00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:48.690
is one of your main points.

00:00:48.690 --> 00:00:51.750
And dinner just
sounds so traditional.

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:53.360
We sit down to dinner.

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:56.660
Grandma, mom, makes
a roast chicken.

00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:59.860
But why is eating
dinner together now

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:01.670
such a revolutionary act?

00:01:01.670 --> 00:01:03.600
You've put it on
these pages for us.

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:04.489
Can you tell us?

00:01:04.489 --> 00:01:06.197
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: It's
interesting to kind

00:01:06.197 --> 00:01:10.850
of frame food in a lot of the
different areas of our lives

00:01:10.850 --> 00:01:14.470
and of global issues that
sometimes food doesn't

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:16.080
get kind of plugged into.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:18.500
Obviously we know that food
is incredibly connected

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:20.940
to our health, and our
personal health, and maybe even

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:22.030
community health.

00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:24.150
But sometimes we miss a
lot of the other elements

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:25.820
that food brings us to.

00:01:25.820 --> 00:01:28.350
And in this book I talk
a lot about politics--

00:01:28.350 --> 00:01:29.820
big, global politics issues.

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:33.450
But also even relationships
at a much more personal level.

00:01:33.450 --> 00:01:37.520
And so dinner is such
an iconic example

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:41.840
of when the family-- the
very small body politic--

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:43.750
gets together and talks.

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:46.550
And the family life
is really borne

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:49.490
from that experience of spending
time together, and talking

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:51.490
and learning, and learning
about family history,

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:53.660
and learning about
the food itself.

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:57.250
And it's really something
that many of us have lost.

00:01:57.250 --> 00:02:00.070
And I think that that can
then be sort of extrapolated

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:01.860
to a lot of other
big picture issues.

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:05.550
Where if this meal is something
that we think of as just a

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:08.900
throwaway, cheap, pick
up on the way home,

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:10.539
drive-through-- well
think about what

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:12.260
that's done to
culture in general,

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:14.720
and then to a lot of these
other big global issues.

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:17.490
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think the
very radical act of sitting down

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:22.920
with people you live with or
care about is so compelling now

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:27.000
in the days when people stand
by their kitchen sink and eat.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.830
Or as you say, drive by.

00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:31.110
Or don't even eat.

00:02:31.110 --> 00:02:32.870
Maybe it's just a snack.

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:36.030
Maybe it's a piece
of something that you

00:02:36.030 --> 00:02:41.160
can put boiling water on and be
through eating in five minutes.

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:42.340
What brought you to this?

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:45.245
Why did you put it at
the center of your life?

00:02:45.245 --> 00:02:46.870
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Well
I didn't actually

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:49.640
start working on
food issues as all.

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:50.670
I'm myself an eater.

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:51.420
I love to eat.

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:53.580
And I think as a
woman-- especially

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.830
as a young woman--
eating actually

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:57.810
posed a lot of
challenges for me.

00:02:57.810 --> 00:02:59.990
I mean, even just
fitting into your jeans

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:03.069
is challenging in our
modern culture of food.

00:03:03.069 --> 00:03:05.360
And so that was always
something in the back of my head

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:07.680
just as a young person
growing up in America,

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.540
and being frustrated that
you hit a point where

00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:11.300
everyone notices.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:13.080
OK, I guess you're
going to be at the age

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:15.038
now where you're going
to start gaining weight.

00:03:15.038 --> 00:03:16.800
And that seems like
a foregone conclusion

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.340
in our modern society.

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:19.520
Which is silly.

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:20.740
It shouldn't be the case.

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:22.830
But actually my work--
my professional life

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:25.450
and my focus-- was much
more on big global issues

00:03:25.450 --> 00:03:27.660
like terrorism and
security issues.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.310
And when I was in a senior
at college in New York City,

00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:32.910
9/11 happened.

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:35.100
I was very, very focused
on understanding terrorism

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:38.210
and why these things
happen in the world,

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:40.670
and what's gone on in
our modern society that

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:43.300
led to this really radical
shift in people's beliefs

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:45.550
about Americans and
about Western culture.

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:47.550
And actually those
two things together

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:48.800
brought me to my current work.

00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:52.320
And it seems kind of crazy,
but in one of my jobs

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:54.880
working on terrorism issues
as an investigative reporter,

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:59.780
I was looking at the global
map of terrorism and places

00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:02.020
where terrorist
groups are operating.

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:06.510
And I also randomly saw this map
from the World Food Program--

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:08.300
the hunger map.

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:11.170
And I noticed that, my God,
they're incredibly similar.

00:04:11.170 --> 00:04:13.440
Places around the world
where people are hungry

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.870
are always connected to
places around the world

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:18.344
where people are violent,
and uprisings occur,

00:04:18.344 --> 00:04:20.750
and terrorism then eventually
festers and happens.

00:04:20.750 --> 00:04:24.150
And that to me was such
an unbelievable link

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:26.917
and connection, and
it led me to switch

00:04:26.917 --> 00:04:29.250
from working on terrorism to
working on fundamental food

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:31.690
security and hunger,
and kind of move along

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:33.630
in my career in a
totally different way.

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:35.130
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
interesting to me

00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:38.610
that you went from
the sexier topic

00:04:38.610 --> 00:04:41.210
of-- if you will-- terrorism.

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:43.170
If it bleeds, it leads.

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:48.730
Kind of investigative reportage
that brought you to this way

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:52.294
quieter, less sexy subject,
but so fundamental.

00:04:52.294 --> 00:04:53.460
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Absolutely.

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:55.690
FEMALE SPEAKER: To
culture, society, politics.

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:56.606
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Yeah.

00:04:56.606 --> 00:04:58.060
I mean, people miss that.

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:00.570
We think of the after-effects.

00:05:00.570 --> 00:05:02.341
How are we going to
fight these people?

00:05:02.341 --> 00:05:03.840
How are we going
to fight terrorism?

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:05.859
And not maybe the
fundamental issues

00:05:05.859 --> 00:05:07.150
of how are we going to prevent?

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:09.650
It's actually the same thing we
look at when we look at health.

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:11.270
Instead of thinking of how
we're going to prevent disease,

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.145
we think of how we're
going to fight disease.

00:05:13.145 --> 00:05:15.620
And it's this whole look at
fighting the problem after it

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:17.411
happens, instead of
preventing these issues

00:05:17.411 --> 00:05:18.710
from ever happening again.

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:20.751
FEMALE SPEAKER: So all
the downstream things that

00:05:20.751 --> 00:05:22.482
are so much more easy
to talk about then

00:05:22.482 --> 00:05:23.440
the fundamental things.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:24.590
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Right exactly.

00:05:24.590 --> 00:05:25.090
Exactly.

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:26.490
FEMALE SPEAKER: So OK.

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:27.830
9/11.

00:05:27.830 --> 00:05:29.790
Tell us a little of the
personal journey that

00:05:29.790 --> 00:05:31.165
brought you to
what you do today.

00:05:31.165 --> 00:05:32.990
Because you have
done so many things.

00:05:32.990 --> 00:05:34.220
You're called an activist.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:36.270
But you're really
a person who cares

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:37.779
so much about
fundamental values.

00:05:37.779 --> 00:05:38.820
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: So yeah.

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:40.361
I didn't really
start as an activist.

00:05:40.361 --> 00:05:43.370
I shifted over from my
work as a journalist

00:05:43.370 --> 00:05:45.520
to the UN World
Food Program itself,

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.600
working in the organization.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:50.620
It's the largest humanitarian
organization in the world.

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:54.170
And I started my job there as
a public information officer,

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:55.354
as a spokesperson.

00:05:55.354 --> 00:05:57.270
And so one of my jobs
was talking to the media

00:05:57.270 --> 00:05:58.590
and getting to
understand hunger,

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:00.173
and why they should
care about hunger.

00:06:00.173 --> 00:06:02.140
And of course I always
brought in this angle

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:04.080
that we should care about hunger
because we care about terrorism

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:05.460
and the downstream effects.

00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:07.700
But also we were
looking for ways

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:09.530
to get young people
engaged in hunger.

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:12.400
Actually, when I started
working there in 2006,

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:15.610
although food security now
is maybe a little bit sexier,

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:18.230
it really wasn't at all then.

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:21.340
And I met one of the
celebrity ambassadors

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:24.470
that was representing the
UN World Food Program.

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:26.630
And she and I kind of
developed this idea

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:31.740
to start a company that sold
products-- the products were

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:36.280
called feed bag-- and each
feed bag sold would give money

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:38.975
back to the UN World Food
Program to raise money

00:06:38.975 --> 00:06:41.100
and to raise awareness
about the problem of hunger,

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:44.500
and let people have a
tangible way to give.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:45.360
It's funny.

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:48.010
We started this company in
a complete vacuum really.

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:49.620
In New York, but
not really knowing

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:50.745
there was a whole movement.

00:06:50.745 --> 00:06:53.717
And Tom's Shoes-- this
other iconic accessories

00:06:53.717 --> 00:06:55.300
brand about giving
back-- was starting

00:06:55.300 --> 00:06:56.370
at the exact same time.

00:06:56.370 --> 00:06:58.815
So there was almost
this zeitgeist

00:06:58.815 --> 00:07:00.940
happening around this whole
social entrepreneurship

00:07:00.940 --> 00:07:03.190
movement, and caring
about global issues,

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:04.660
but through your
consumer dollars.

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:08.070
And so starting Feed was
a huge, huge thing for me.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:12.045
It was an incredible experience
running a business, a fashion

00:07:12.045 --> 00:07:13.420
business, but also
getting people

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:15.690
to care through their
consumer purchases

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:17.450
about this issue of hunger.

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:21.980
But eventually as my years
working on global hunger

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:25.290
continued, I had this aha
moment that I talk about

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:29.170
in the book where I
was in Uganda working

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:31.200
on hunger issues,
as you might expect.

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:35.480
And I went into a
store to get food

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:38.640
to take with me out to a
day's work in the field--

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.550
while visiting projects
that we were funding,

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:43.530
and visiting different things
that aid organizations were

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:44.140
working on.

00:07:44.140 --> 00:07:48.390
And going into a little store
in this small city in Uganda.

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:50.150
I mean, really not Kumpala.

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:51.470
Not [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:52.980
Not one of the main cities.

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:56.270
And it was literally
packed with junk.

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:58.590
And I remember driving
through these dirt roads.

00:07:58.590 --> 00:08:00.420
There's soda.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:01.639
Pringles are everywhere.

00:08:01.639 --> 00:08:03.180
I don't know how
they get everywhere.

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:05.200
There's ice cream
in so many places

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:08.030
that have barely safe water.

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:14.260
And chips and packaged
sweets and pastries.

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:18.590
And I was like how have we
got somehow, this system where

00:08:18.590 --> 00:08:20.490
we can get people
Coca-Cola literally

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:23.510
in 200 countries, more countries
than are recognized by the UN,

00:08:23.510 --> 00:08:27.220
and somehow we can't get
healthy basic food that's

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:28.000
grown locally.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.770
And it really struck me when
I flew back to the States

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:33.480
and went into one of those
Hudson new stores, that

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:36.960
are in every airport, and
it's literally all junk.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:38.600
It's the same stuff.

00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:41.340
And I had this aha moment
of like, wait a minute.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.570
This is much more similar
than it is different.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:46.915
Our problems at home of obesity
and fitting into our jeans,

00:08:46.915 --> 00:08:49.290
and everybody gaining weight,
and all the health problems

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:50.260
related to that.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:52.019
And this hunger
problem that I've

00:08:52.019 --> 00:08:53.560
been working that
seemed so far away,

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:56.259
are so much more similar
than they are different.

00:08:56.259 --> 00:08:58.800
And then I started working on
the connection between the two.

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:00.637
And eventually this book.

00:09:00.637 --> 00:09:01.720
FEMALE SPEAKER: Beautiful.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:04.520
So it's malnutrition.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:06.329
It's eating bad food.

00:09:06.329 --> 00:09:07.370
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Exactly.

00:09:07.370 --> 00:09:10.050
FEMALE SPEAKER: Food that
causes disease, and doesn't

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.230
maintain and sustain you.

00:09:12.230 --> 00:09:13.390
What a journey.

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:17.027
And Feed-- did I read
that you fed 6 million?

00:09:17.027 --> 00:09:18.110
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Well yes.

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:20.360
So actually, the
numbers today of Feed--

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:22.340
which has continued and
been really successful

00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:25.670
over the years since we
started in 2007-- they've

00:09:25.670 --> 00:09:29.962
provided 80 million school
meals to kids around the world.

00:09:29.962 --> 00:09:31.670
And while I was there,
it was 60 million.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:32.990
So the numbers keep going.

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:36.970
And what's interesting too,
the timing of my own journey

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:40.686
is while I was at Feed--
started in 2006-- in 2008,

00:09:40.686 --> 00:09:42.060
there was this
global food crisis

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:44.300
and hunger was skyrocketing.

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:46.420
And so we were at our best year.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:50.040
We are providing so many
millions of school meals.

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:52.750
But the problem of hunger
was growing so dramatically.

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:54.500
And it really made
me think that there's

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:55.820
something so much bigger here.

00:09:55.820 --> 00:09:57.912
The system is
really the problem.

00:09:57.912 --> 00:10:00.370
This is not something that we
can just only throw money at.

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:02.240
We have to figure
out fundamentally

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:05.114
how to change this system.

00:10:05.114 --> 00:10:07.280
FEMALE SPEAKER: And how
should we change the system?

00:10:07.280 --> 00:10:09.292
Where should each
one of us begin?

00:10:09.292 --> 00:10:11.000
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Well
it comes eventually

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:12.420
through thinking,
and researching,

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:13.560
and writing this book.

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:15.750
But also just really
deeply looking

00:10:15.750 --> 00:10:18.300
at how the interconnection
between our food system at home

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:22.180
and these food systems I've
seen overseas is-- Americans

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:24.500
decide what the world eats.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:26.970
And the more you travel,
the more you see it.

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:29.330
In countries and cultures
that people have always

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:33.410
eaten incredible traditional
diets, and diverse crops

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:37.010
from their own regions and
soils, now more and more,

00:10:37.010 --> 00:10:38.620
it's what we eat.

00:10:38.620 --> 00:10:42.060
And its our varieties, and
it's our agricultural systems,

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:44.500
and it made me
think that Americans

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:46.290
have a huge responsibility.

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:47.290
Hence "We the Eaters."

00:10:47.290 --> 00:10:51.140
We have a huge
responsibility to understand

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:53.640
that our eating
habits themselves

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:55.270
have a massive impact
around the world.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:59.300
And if we don't get them
right-- if we export the junk

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:00.800
food and the fast
food and the soda,

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:02.527
as we have been
doing-- that is what

00:11:02.527 --> 00:11:03.860
the world is going to look like.

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:06.536
They're going to look just like
us as they're starting to do.

00:11:06.536 --> 00:11:08.160
And so if we get it
right here at home,

00:11:08.160 --> 00:11:10.290
if we figure out how
to make a system work,

00:11:10.290 --> 00:11:12.661
like we figured out how to
get cell phones to be really

00:11:12.661 --> 00:11:15.160
successful, and now there's
more African cellphone consumers

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:17.284
than there are North American
cell phone consumers.

00:11:17.284 --> 00:11:18.810
We can do that
with food systems.

00:11:18.810 --> 00:11:20.590
We just haven't
figured out yet how.

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:22.520
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think
China and India are

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:25.044
vying for diabetes
capital of the world.

00:11:25.044 --> 00:11:25.960
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Yeah.

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:26.580
Mexico.

00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:28.420
I mean, all these countries.

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:31.610
And it's not because their
own people are somehow

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:34.760
changed and lazy, like
the messaging we hear.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:36.530
And their personal
responsibility

00:11:36.530 --> 00:11:37.580
has gone down the toilet.

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:39.038
No it's because
they're eating more

00:11:39.038 --> 00:11:40.254
and more of the Western diet.

00:11:40.254 --> 00:11:41.920
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's
the fast food diet.

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:49.330
And it fits in such a
weird way and so quickly

00:11:49.330 --> 00:11:50.210
into their cultures.

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:53.740
I think what it took
America since the '50s

00:11:53.740 --> 00:11:57.340
in the last century to do,
it's taken them 10, 20 years

00:11:57.340 --> 00:12:00.075
to get to this place of
disease and non-health.

00:12:00.075 --> 00:12:01.700
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: Well
and the flip side

00:12:01.700 --> 00:12:06.180
of that is that we built this
system-- the fast food system,

00:12:06.180 --> 00:12:09.519
the soda system, the junk
food proliferation system.

00:12:09.519 --> 00:12:10.560
And it works really well.

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:12.320
And we've perfected it.

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:13.880
And now it works really well.

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:16.410
And so there is
absolutely no reason

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:18.440
we can't do that
with healthy foods.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:20.274
It's not like a
foregone conclusion

00:12:20.274 --> 00:12:21.690
that this is the
only food that we

00:12:21.690 --> 00:12:26.410
can make in a way that's
produced and available.

00:12:26.410 --> 00:12:27.860
The systems have
to be different,

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:31.340
but we can-- and actually
here we are in the Bay Area,

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:34.660
and we can see that the
alternative can work.

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:37.600
In almost every small
place you go into now

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:40.020
in the San Francisco
Bay Area has

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:41.580
some semblance of
local purchasing,

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:45.447
or healthier food, or
green juice, or kale.

00:12:45.447 --> 00:12:47.280
FEMALE SPEAKER: And
more kale and more kale.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:48.130
ELLEN GUSTAFSON: And
more kale and more kale.

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:50.750
And so the fact is, we can
make these systems work

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:52.080
for healthier foods.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:54.340
It's just a matter
of the entrepreneurs

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:59.250
and the eaters joining forces
to make the better system work.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:01.830
FEMALE SPEAKER: It is going to
look different though, right?

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:05.220
You envision a future where we
